Duck Typing is a concept in object-oriented programming that states that if an object walks like a duck and quacks like a duck, then it is a duck. In other words, an object is considered to be of a certain type if it behaves like an object of that type. This is in contrast to static typing, where the type of an object is determined by its class or interface.

In TypeScript, Duck Typing is used in conjunction with interfaces. An interface in TypeScript is a way to define the shape of an object, including its properties and methods. When an object is used in a context where an interface is expected, TypeScript will check if the object has the required properties and methods. If it does, it will be considered to be of the expected type, even if it is not explicitly declared to be of that type.

For example, consider the following TypeScript code:

```typescript
interface Bird {
    fly(): void;
    quack(): void;
}

function flyTheBird(bird: Bird) {
    bird.fly();
    bird.quack();
}

class Duck implements Bird {
    fly() {
        console.log("I'm flying!");
    }
    quack() {
        console.log("Quack!");
    }
}

let duck = new Duck();
flyTheBird(duck);
```

